segments.text: If they couldn't step into that kind of a position, then we were competitive because they wanted to go to a university to work.
And we had some people from Lamar and other universities in Texas that were interested in coming on board with us.
So we were probably in between, probably in between the
the Southwest Texas, Lamar, and lower than the University of Texas, Michigan, and Columbia.
We were probably in between.
Do you remember some steps of accomplishment that in hindsight you now realize were key steps of progress during those early years?
Yeah, I think this block program
began to blossom and we would eventually begin to see what was called a professional senior semester program where students would have an increased amount of time in student teaching.
But they didn't have to worry about going off to other departments for courses.
They could take this as a block
and they could do a lot of their work out in the public school setting and almost spend, after the first, say, six weeks on campus, they could almost spend the entire
day, five days a week out in the public school setting, finishing coursework, doing student teaching, and so forth.
And that program, I thought, was very good.
It gave them an edge.
Any number of personnel from public school systems were telling us over and over, they wanted our students because they liked what they were getting.

If they ever got one of our students, they were back for more because I think that gave them an edge being out in the public school setting for that length of time instead of just going out, running out and teaching a course or teaching classes for an hour or two and then running back to campus to take a course and then the next day
running out there and then coming back the next day and taking a course.
It was too fragmented.

This gave them the full-blown picture because, for example, if they were doing all of this in the fall, they had to go out before, even if we weren't open yet at the university, they had to go out and participate in the opening preparation days of the school.
They followed
the public school schedule, not our schedule, so to speak.
And so they really understood what education was all about when they finished.
And we were proud of them.
I'd say that was a key factor.
I think another two key factors that I really enjoyed watching grow was the whole shift now when it came to the doctoral program.
particularly the dissertation area.
The dissertation became more refined.
It became more specialized, more in-depth.

And when our students finished, we really felt confident that they go out and whatever they were doing their research in, they could step in and pick that up immediately and run with it, regardless of where they went.
And a lot of them did end up going to major universities because of that.
The other major shift that I saw that was good was the shift to
paying more attention to research grants, getting money from federal sources, private sources to run their research.
When I first came, that was very, very small.
It wasn't a very large amount.
Frank Hubert and Earl Jones had hit on some pretty big programs, creative application of technology to education.
But other than a couple of those kinds of programs, the research dollars weren't flowing in.
I appreciated seeing that grow.
Were you in the department, was the department also responsible for the work and practice teaching?
Did you all supervise that out in the local schools?
Yes.
With which schools did you all most?
Just about every one of them in Bryan College Station because we had so many.
But primarily these two school districts?
Primarily here.
Eventually we, they didn't have enough

enough places and we had to start reaching out beyond here to Somerville, Conroe, and then further down the pike we even had to establish programs with as far away as the Dallas area and so forth to get some
How difficult was it to establish a new relationship with the school district?
Pretty easy.
Again, I think that whole experience with Frank Hubert and Paul Hensarling, people like Les Richardson and so forth, paid off that way.
I think these were...
people who were well known among the public school people.
And so they were pretty open about discussing with us possibilities of placing student teachers and then grabbing them.
They liked our student teachers too.
Can you remember any anecdotes or stories about where some Aggie student teachers succeeded?
Where somebody had an example of the quality of one of the student teachers from here, something they did?
No, that one doesn't come across to me.
Now we had lots of success as far as our doctoral students going out.
I had just the ones I chaired, for example.
One became vice president of McMurray State.
Another one became president of a junior college.
Wait, let's go back up.
You said McMurray State.
Isn't it?
McMurray, Abilene?
Just McMurray.
McMurray.
Okay, yeah, that's right.
Murray State is a Kentucky Teachers College.
That's right.
Others that you can recall down through the years and where they are now?
Yeah, one of the stars to come out of the program, I thought, was Cecil Drain.
Cecil had...
been in the military and was kind of predicted to go pretty far in the military.
He was already a major.
when he came into residence on his doctorate, and they funded, the military funded him everything for three full years at a major salary, and he got a promotion to lieutenant colonel.
He went back to San Antonio and worked with the, at Fort Hood down there, teaching in the field of anesthetism.
And when he retired from the military, he immediately stepped in as head of the Department of Allied Health and Anesthesia and so forth at Virginia Commonwealth University.
So he was really... And he had written books.
He had books that were the Bible in the military as far as...
operating room functioning and anesthesia and so forth.
He was actually the author of the books that they were using to train people with.
So Cecil was a big star.
Public school wise, Libby Gardner comes to mind.
Libby
finished her doctoral program with us and stepped in as an assistant principal over in Conroe and then became a principal and then assistant superintendent.
She's down in Conroe ISD.
There have been a lot of examples like that where
They've been pretty successful.
Right.
You were department head for five years.
Five years.
And so that takes us to 72 or three.
Seventy-four.
Four.
Yeah.
Then you become the, what was the term?
Coordinator for higher education in the College of Education.
And you did that how long?
Did that until, let's see, 1980, when Chuck McCandless and Gordon Eaton and Frank Vandiver were the three administrative types at the university level.
And I'd been working with Frank Hubert trying to get a center established for assisting faculty and teaching assistants in teaching.
And when Dean Corrigan came in as the new Dean of College of Ed, he picked up on that.
and convinced people we needed that.
That's when McCandless headed up a committee that I served on for about a year with representatives from all the colleges.
Out of that grew the proposal to open the Texas A&M University Center for Teaching Excellence.
Vandiver asked me if I would head that up.

Then I gave up the coordinating role of higher education in the college because I would be carrying on my responsibilities in the college as far as course teaching and doctoral students, but then half my time would be in the Center for Teaching Excellence.
I did that.
From what, 1980 to, must have been about 89, somewhere around there that I stepped out of that role.
Right, now Hubert goes from being dean of education to chancellor.
Yes.
Directly.
Yeah.
And he continued to function until that change.
In the college, and the college continued to grow and so forth.
Yes.
Who else in the 70s, Williams being the president from late November 1970 until his illness in 1976,
Do you remember any interaction with Williams, the Williams, Calhoun, Hubert leadership team?
I never had that kind of, you know, I wasn't in that loop, so I don't know what was transpiring.
But I did get acquainted with Jack Kenny Williams, and...
I can remember being surprised.
We'd played golf together out at Briarcrest Country Club.

members out of Briarcrest and one day we got hooked up to play golf and the next week I got a little note from Jack Kenny Williams just saying, you know, I hope you're enjoying hitting the little white ball, you know, type of thing.
And that impressed me that a president would take time after meeting a faculty member like that.
He was marvelous with those little notes.
and they were always handwritten and very much to the point but carried a message because I remember treasuring a few of those also.
What was your impression of him as a human being?
Oh, only positive.
He epitomized to me what a university president should be.
I think he had the credentials for it, too, and the experience.
He had been, what, vice president at the University of Texas at Tennessee at Knoxville?
The system.
Chief academic officer for the system.

Started out at Clemson as an entry-level Southern history faculty member and rose up to be what we would today call provost and then commissioner of higher education, but also was very, very, very committed to helping the Southern
historically black land grant schools during his Clemson years.
And so all across the South, he was known by that group of schools with great warmth as well.
And through that and his Clemson experience, he had lots of Washington connections.
Okay.
Did you feel that he was strongly supportive of education?
I did.
I felt he was.
And I think Frank Humer felt that way, too.
As far as I know, he certainly was.
And I felt that way too with Chuck McCandless and Gordon Eaton when they were over in the provost's office.
That was just a feeling I had that they were supportive.
Do you remember any examples of that?

Well, the whole thing with the Center for Teaching Excellence, I think Chuck McCandless, and then when Gordon came in as the new provost, Chuck was serving at the beginning of that work as interim provost, as I recall.
There just seemed to be an agreement between them two that this was something they wanted to see.
I always had the impression that they were very positive toward education.
I think during those first
15 years or so, it just seemed like everyone wanted this college of education to really be successful.
Even if you looked at the financial allocations to the colleges, we were almost always right smack in the middle.
There were always
half the colleges that were getting less support, it seemed like.
Of course, engineering and veterinary medicine, we're always getting a lot of support and so forth.
But we seemed to be doing pretty well.
And I attribute that to the administration at the time, from the provost on up, that they were supportive.
Any examples you remember of the positive actions of
John Calhoun or Mac Prescott when they were the chief academic officers.
I never really, I knew both and had interacted because of committee functions that I was on.
But I never really again had, I guess again by that time I was out of what you would call the loop where you were now finding out who was saying what and doing what and so forth.
So I don't recall anything that I can share with you in that area.

My mind just recalls a legend that I remember hearing very, very, very indirectly about a faculty member in education, and I know not what department, who supposedly came with a thick resume with all kinds of bells and whistles and was verbally abusive to students, always putting them down, always insulting them, and that as we heard the story, two or three of the students got his resume and went over to the library and
and found that nothing in the printed resume of his publications and research matched up with what they could find in the library.
And that according to this anecdote, they slid it under the door of the dean of education, Frank Hubert.
Hubert then summoned the man to his office and asked him what comment he had to make of it.
And the fellow was gone by...
within a few hours.
Does that ring a bell at all?
No, it really doesn't.
And it may not have been a true story, but it sounded... Well, that's another one you really...
I would like to hear what Frank Hubert has to say.
That's a great story.
Let me throw in this one, which does not relate to education.
In my years as dean of faculties, I would ask each of the departments to let me have 30 minutes...

of every prospective faculty member's visit to the campus, during which time I would try to tell them as much as I could and give them as much positive information, factual information, about what A&M really was and what it hoped to become.
And among things I would say is that A&M is a comparatively conservative
institution, and I mean by that that it doesn't change rapidly.
We kind of go by tradition.
And that if they wanted a real liberal school, they might not like us.
And I would always assure the departments I would in no way try to evaluate the individuals.
But it worked out that about once a year, I encountered somebody that really seemed to need some other review.
And the one that I'm thinking about now particularly, his resume said he had a PhD from the University of Virginia.
And I mentioned having done research at the Alderman Library.
and he didn't know where it was.
Well that was the, that is the library.
So then on the spur of the moment I made up the names of three or four non-existent people that I knew in the department where he had done his dissertation.
He knew all three of them quite well.
So I called the department after he left the office and told them what had happened.
They then called the University of Virginia and found that they had never heard
of this man who claimed to have a degree from that school.
Now you became a legend yourself Haskell in that role because everyone appreciated
Your candor and the way you handled candidates who were being interviewed.
Thank you.
And it was.
Thank you.
You really became a legend.
People just admired that and respected it.
We're thankful to you for doing what you were doing.
All right, let's go near the... As Hubert begins to reach... No, no, he didn't retire.
He moved upstairs.
All right, as he goes up to be the chancellor of the system...
What did you and your colleagues think about the Dean of Education ascending that far up?
Of course, we were very positive.
We liked that.
But the day that happened, and Frank Hubert talked to me later, and he can clarify this for you, but
There was a committee meeting to be held like 9 o'clock that morning in his office, the dean's conference room.
And we were all assembled up there.
It may have been a department heads meeting, for all I know.
We're all assembled up there.
And Frank Hubert, who is very prompt, wasn't there.
And all of a sudden, Peggy Ritchie, his secretary, comes in.
She says, Dr. Johnson?
Dean Hubert said, you're in charge of this meeting.
OK.
So I took charge of the meeting.
And then later, probably that same day, the word trickled out that Frank Hubert was going to become chancellor of the system.
And probably that same day, maybe, he talked to me.
And this was the story, I think, as I best recall it.
They were looking for a new chancellor.
And occasionally, they would call Frank in and ask him for advice on how to go about this.
Did he have anyone in mind?
What did he think about person X or person Y?
And apparently, this had gone on a couple of times.
And this particular morning, he got a phone call from the chair of the Board of Regents.
And it went something like, Frank, can you join us for breakfast at 7 o'clock?
And Frank said, yes.
And he went into that meeting thinking, oh, they've got somebody they want to ask me about.
And they said, Frank, we want you to be the chancellor.
And as I recall, he said, can I have a couple of hours?
I need to think about this.
I need to get home.
Talk to Mary Julia, etc.
And that's probably when he called over and told Peggy, you know, tell Glenn to take charge of that committee meeting.
And he went home and talked it over and came back and accepted and became the chancellor.
And as he had

done so many times remember I told you earlier that thing I liked about Frank Hubert as I did seem to see with Benson they delegated and and almost immediately you know Frank Hubert was saying okay you guys take over now the college I'm going to be the chancellor
And I'm going to do this thing up here kind of thing.
And you can kind of review that with Frank.
But that's my recollection that he was completely taken aback and caught completely off guard and surprised.
Who then took over the college even on an interim basis?
Oh, boy.
Let's see.
Was it Phil?
I think it may have been Phil Limbacher.

who was the assistant dean assistant dean and i think he became interim dean and served in that role until we brought corrigan in right now i chaired that search committee wonderful job again you see you did something now maybe you learned this from frank hubert for all i know or benson or some of these people

But you made it very clear to us that we were the ones who were going to carry the ball on this and find out everything we could about these candidates and that we would be really the ones who would make the recommendation and you would take that forward.
You said you might have to go forward with two or three and prioritize them, but we were going to carry the ball on that.
And I think as a result of that,

we ended up with a really fine dean and Dean Corrigan because I think in the past there had been times when it hadn't been handled that way and new deans came in and they weren't that successful as Corrigan was but I know in Corrigan's case he was up against some pretty stiff competition uh we had four candidates that we brought in
One was president of the International Reading Association with a fine credentials out of Indiana University, as I recall, or Illinois, one of the two, probably Illinois.
The dean of education at Ohio State University.
The vice president for Stony Brook and the New York system.
And Corrigan, dean at the University of Maryland.
When I went through their credentials,

I ranked, ordered them, number one, Dean at Ohio State, number two, Vice President Stony Brook, number three, Corrigan Dean at Maryland, and fourth, President of the International Reading Association.
By the time we finished interviewing those four, there was no doubt in my mind and in most of the committee members that one person was a full cut above.
the other three, and that was Dean Corrigan.
And so we put our faith in him and said we want him.
There was a play.

out of some of the representatives from health and physical education for the vice president from Stony Brook because he had, I believe it was an undergraduate degree in health and physical education.
So they kept pushing, Miller I believe was his name, they kept pushing Miller for that job.
But the overwhelming number of us, as I recall, when you started counting hands when they went up, it was just overwhelmingly Corrigan.

among things that i tried to do in that and other searches was that each of the candidates would go through exactly the same schedule hopefully in the same order in the same places with the same people present and that the interviewing groups would try to compose
and agree upon the questions they were going to emphasize well in advance so that they would be pretty well measuring them the same way.

And with Corrigan, I particularly remember picking him up at the airport about two hours after I had come back from my first interview visit to the University of Texas at El Paso as a potential president.
And I was worn out physically and emotionally.
And I took him to meet with the entire faculty.
And when I sat down, I thought, boy, Mr.
Visitor, you better be pretty good or I'll probably go to sleep.
Well, of course, by the end of an hour or two of him, I was wide awake.
and much impressed with him.
But I felt very optimistic at the start, and thank goodness that optimism was fulfilled.
What were his key attributes?
Well, I think personality was overwhelmingly the key factor.
He knew how to relate to people.
He was very empathetic.
understood education and the College of Education, had been extremely active on the national scene, was president of one of the major organizations in education.
Striking contrast with Frank Hubert, as far as administrative style goes, where Frank was more of a

organization delegate hold responsible type of thing Corrigan was more of let's be friends and let's talk about this and is there something I can do you know to move this along etc etc and I think just as Rudder was the right man for president of the University and then Jack Kenny Williams in that order and as we mentioned earlier
Probably wouldn't have worked if it had been reversed.
So it was, I think, in the case of Hubert and Corrigan.
I'm not sure that the Corrigan deanship would have been the right one when we got started, but Hubert was.
But I'm not sure that Hubert would have been the right one after the establishment of the college.
Could have been.
But Corrigan was the right one to follow Hubert and bring this personal touch and support throughout the college.
Now, Corrigan would serve for?
Ten years.
Ten years.
Okay, so he and Hubert then both a long time.
As far as you could generalize, when Corrigan began his deanship,
At what level was our College of Education in national or local or regional competition, and where was it when he stepped away?
I would say when we opened our doors and after the first year or two, we were probably in the bottom 20%, 25% nationally.
And I would say by the time Hubert finished his tenure and then Corrigan finished his tenure, we had moved up to the top 25%.
We're not a top 10.
We're not top 20.
But at least to me.
